Why Jerome Powell Must Go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to possibly the most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here could have grave consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, paving the way for the worst economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political leaders' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; it exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are many clichés about why the current head of the Federal Reserve, Jerome Powell, should be confirmed in his position.
It would be a proof of non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
We would use someone with experience who leads us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I heard 25 years ago when I was the chairman of the economic advisory board to US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan remained a topic.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid dearly for its decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied him a second term after Volcker had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed much to Volcker but sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an adherent of Ayn Rand.
Economic policy requires careful assessment and sensitivity to goal conflicts.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that the markets alone are efficient, stable, fair, and competitive?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the USA have always expressed clearly articulated, but markedly different views on these issues (at least until the Republicans succumbed to populist delusions).
In my view, the Democrats have legitimate concerns about the consequences of unemployment.
The crisis of 2008 showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally, only under strained labor markets do marginalized groups get incorporated into the national economy and wage differentials reduced.
The coming years will likely be a test for every US central bank chief.
Already now, the United States are facing difficult decisions regarding what to do against inflation.
Are the recent price increases mainly minor issues arising from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed consider the unemployment rate among African Americans, who have yet to regain their pre-pandemic levels?
Would interest rate hikes (and thus an increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While mispricing with mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the crisis of 2008, there are now indications of even more widespread and pervasive mispricing linked to climate change affecting asset values.
What should the Fed do about this?
Powell is not the man for the job.
Zunächst unterstützte er die Deregulierungsagenda von Ex-Präsident Donald Trump und riskierte damit die finanzielle Gesundheit unserer Welt.
Und selbst jetzt zögert er, etwas in Bezug auf das Klimarisiko zu unternehmen, obwohl andere Notenbanker weltweit dieses inzwischen zum zentralen Problem der kommenden Jahrzehnte erklärt haben.
Powell würde argumentieren, dass Klimafragen nicht zum Mandat der Fed gehören, doch damit hätte er Unrecht.
Es gehört zum Auftrag der Fed, Finanzstabilität zu gewährleisten, und es gibt keine größere Gefahr für die Finanzstabilität als den Klimawandel.
Die Fed ist zudem dafür verantwortlich, Fusionen im Finanzsektor zu genehmigen, und Powells Bilanz dabei legt nahe, dass er noch nie eine schlechte Fusion erlebt hat.
A such laxity is the last thing that the economy currently needs.
An egregious lack of competition and the absence of adequate regulation already enable excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's reaction to the pandemic.
Yet any second-year student would have known that monetary policy cannot be tightened and interest rates raised during a recession.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argues, Powell does not feel particularly obligated to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's tenure as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board in terms of tightening monetary policy over the last decade has been marked by a series of misjudgments that go back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
While many observers of the Fed maintain that inequality is not the bank's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policy has significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as raising interest rates too early can stifle growth, weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for greater market concentration.
Finally, the recent scandal involving trading by leading Fed representatives has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparently lacking awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has long troubled me.
Nachdem vier Jahre Trump das Vertrauen in die US-Institutionen bereits geschwächt haben, besteht nun ein echtes Risiko, dass das Vertrauen in die Integrität der Notenbank weiter leidet.
Kein Fed-Vertreter sollte einen Ethikbeauftragten brauchen, der entscheidet, wann bestimmte Börsengeschäfte unziemlich erscheinen würden.
Die Fed ähnelt in gewisser Hinsicht dem US Supreme Court.
Dieser soll über der Politik stehen, doch spätestens seit Bush v. Gore wissen wir, dass das nicht der Fall ist.
Trump hat das für alle klargestellt, die noch Zweifel hatten.
Auch die Fed soll angeblich unabhängig sein, jedoch haben Powell und Greenspan, indem sie der Deregulierungsagenda ihrer Partei folgten, klar gezeigt, dass das ebenfalls nicht zutrifft.
Doch während der Notenbankrat wichtige Entscheidungen trifft, die alle Aspekte der Wirtschaft beeinflussen, konzentriert sich die Macht traditionell in den Händen des Notenbankchefs – und zwar viel stärker als beim Gerichtsvorsitzenden des Supreme Court.
Es ist der Notenbankchef, der entscheidet, was zur Abstimmung kommt und welche Themen zurückgestellt oder forciert werden.
Die Klimafrage ist nur ein Beispiel, wo enorm wichtig ist, wer an der Spitze des Tisches sitzt.
Die USA brauchen eine Notenbank, die sich wirklich dazu bekennt, für einen stabilen, fairen, effizienten und wettbewerbsbestimmten Finanzsektor zu sorgen.
Those who believe that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far lack insight.
We do not need an ideologue like Greenspan or a Wall Street-friendly lawyer like Powell.
What is needed is someone who possesses deep economic understanding and shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are certainly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden does not have to look far to find someone whose abilities he has already demonstrated.
Lael Brainard already sits on the Fed's board, where she has demonstrated her expertise and won market confidence – without compromising on her values.
Biden can have both: a Fed chair who delivers continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but also shares his economic and social agenda.
